segments.text: Someone to come in and take over a corporation that was $9 million in debt, that must have taken somewhat of a gambling spirit.
Well, I was 34 years old, and at 34, I was willing to gamble more than I am today.
Did it look like it was a better opportunity than staying with Lone Star Gas?
Well, it did to me, and of course, it was a very fortunate move for me.
But I...
For a period of time, I did wonder whether I had made a mistake, because it was a long way back for a company that had to get started.
I could imagine so, yes.
What would you think would be some of the outstanding developments in your area of petroleum engineering, say, since 1938, that you've come to Shamrock?
Well, of course, my experience in petroleum engineering was largely while I was with the Lone Star Gas Company.
When I came with Diamond Shamrock, my experience was administrative management.
But I imagine you kept up with the developments in the field to a certain extent anyway.
Well, to tell you the truth, there's been so much progress made in that field that I
hardly speak the language anymore.
The science and engineering in the oil industry has advanced beyond belief over this period of time.
You see, in my early experience in the oil business, waste was the rule rather than the exception.
And there was an oversupply of both oil and gas.
And when I came up to Amarillo to work for the Shamrock, oil was selling for 50 cents a barrel and gas at a penny a thousand cubic feet.
And nobody
gave much importance on reserves.
For perspective, what's it selling for today?
Well, the oil is selling for about $10 a barrel, and gas, intrastate gas, is selling for $1,000 and more.
The interstate gas, the price is regulated by the Federal Power Commission
has been adjusted upwards to 45,000 cents per thousand cubic feet.
And there's not much gas available at that price.
So it's an entirely new ballgame.
And in my early experience in the...
oil and gas business, mostly gas, while I was with the Lone Star Gas Company.
I ran experiments and did a lot of development work in the field toward conservation of gas, to cut out the waste of gas, and wrote a number of papers on that subject
during a time when no one seemed to be much interested in conserving gas.
But those practices have developed to where now there's very little waste.
I served as chairman of the engineering committee to study the panhandle waste during the period of time when it was legal to blow gas into the air to get the liquids out.
There's some four billion cubic feet of gas wasted before they were able to get the laws passed to stop the waste.
I testified in the Senate Investigating Committee and the coal committee from Congress investigating that waste.
And finally, in 1935, they repealed the stripping law and cut out this large waste of gas.
but the Railroad Commission had many, many lawsuits from people resisting the law and challenging the law before they ever were able to establish their conservation rules and regulations.
In a way, I guess you could say that between, say, 1938 and now, the biggest change has been, outside of the increased technology, would be
that earlier it was a product looking for a market, and today it's a market looking for a product.
Well, that's true.
That substantially tells the whole story.
And when a commodity becomes valuable, then the industry itself will eliminate the waste because it pays them to do so.
I think the most recent
Our last two former student directories have you in and listed as being involved in ranching and investments.
When did you get into ranching?
About nearly 15 years ago.
And 10 or 12 years ago, when I was getting ready for retirement,
I realized that I would have to have something to keep me busy.
I was interested in ranching, and I've been, although this is not a good year in ranching on account of the drought, it's been a good occupation, a very interesting occupation.
Well, I can imagine where the drought would, drought has been bad in a lot of places, I think.
My father has a small piece of property and runs about 50 cows, and
In addition, I guess, to the drought, there's been a pretty drastic drop in price, hasn't there?
Yes.
Well, from last year to this year, it's just about a little less than half of what it was last year to the producer.
Of course, there are many problems from the cost standpoint.
Feed prices have doubled in the last year, and the cattle prices have halved.
But these cycles have a way of working themselves around.
The most serious problem right now in the cattle business is the drought, the inability to grow the grass that you need, so you have to buy more feed.
My father's property is in Lee County, Texas.
In that area, almost everybody that has any cattle has a stock pond.
or two or three for their cattle for drinking water.
How do you provide water for your cows?
Do you have a stockpile?
I have both.
I have numerous windmills and surface tanks, but the surface tanks are all practically dry right now.
And when the wind doesn't blow, and that's seldom in the panhandle, but right now it hadn't been blowing so much, and I was at the ranch yesterday, and
The windmills weren't turning, and the surface tanks were dry, and so I began to wonder if it was going to rain soon enough, I was going to have to move some cattle.
I can imagine.
By moving, you mean selling them.
I'll move them to other pastures where I still have water.
I see.

Well, I know it was somewhat of a shock to my wife yesterday when we were driving along, and I told her that shortly we'd be crossing the Red River, and she was very disappointed to see that it was dry.
Yeah.
I've seen the Red River on a flood basis.
I had to come to Amarillo one time when I was a Lone Star guest.
I was at one of these hearings, and they had every railroad bridge and every highway bridge between here and Vernon was washed out.
And so the Red River is not always dry.
I'm sure it's not.
Since you graduated from A&M, I think you've kept a fairly close tie with the school.
I believe at one point you served on the board, did you not?
Yes, from 1953 to 59.
What would you say would be the most significant developments that occurred at that period in A&M's history?
Well, it's a little hard since progress is to be effective as a continuous thing.
It's a little hard to pinpoint it, but I served as chairman of the building committee and we didn't have as much money to spend as we needed to build these new buildings
as fast as we'd like to have had them.

Our income from the permanent fund was a good deal less than it is today, and so we established a priority list, the board of directors did, and we reviewed that from time to time, and we took these buildings that we constructed during that period of time
in the order of priorities established by the board of directors.
Now, I see today how much better A&M can function with the facilities that they have been able to establish, particularly in the last decade.

that you can see the effect that quality not only in staff personnel but quality in facilities will do for attracting students when you see that A&M is facing its greatest enrollment of its history this year.
So I'd say that I hope that we got some of these things headed in the right direction.
I'm very proud of the fact that Darryl Rudder came during the time that I was on the board of directors, and he had a great deal of vision.
And we charted the courses that were
expanded and improved upon later for the progress that's been made.
And I might say that I couldn't have a higher regard for the job that Jack Williams is doing as president of the school now.
He has the vision, and he was able to take over and
continue and actually accelerate the progress in these directions that have been established.
And it's all based on quality.
And I hope we never lose it.
Well, I do too.
I've certainly been impressed in the three years that I've been there, because I have known of A&M for many years, having grown up 60 miles south of there.
But it certainly strikes me as being a quality institution.

and I think is exemplified by one of the things which Dr. Williams has said when our former librarian decided, you know, Jack Smith decided to take a job in New York, that Dr. Williams did not say, as some people would have said, well, we've got X number of dollars.
We'll find us a librarian who will come to work for that.
indicated that we would find the librarian we wanted, and then we would pay whatever was necessary to get that person to come.
And I don't know whether you know who the new librarian is or not.
It's a lady from Ohio State.
No, I haven't met him.
And I believe that at least the people in the library are almost universally pleased with the choice.
Of course, the people in the library were very much involved in
making this choice, which I think also is a good move on behalf of the president, that the people under whom this person would work would have a choice in choosing that person.
Well, it  Jack Williams' whole philosophy and his execution of his principles
please me very much.
He's a man who can handle people, a man who has the vision he needs and the educational background that he needs, and I just hope he stays healthy and stays there and have a long time.
Well, I think there are a lot of people who support you in that feeling, Mr. Dunn, and I know I do.
I would imagine that the
The naming of the dormitory for you must have been kind of a highlight of your career.
Yes, it was, and a total surprise.
President Williams called me one day and asked me if I would give my permission for him to name a dormitory after me, just out of the blue sky.
And I said, well, I'd be highly honored.
So that's the way it took place.
Well, I had never heard anybody explain how it took place other than the fact that the board announced that they were naming one dorm for you and one dorm for Mr. Kruger.
And I know he was very much pleased.
I think he said that was the highlight of his life.
The day he spent there during the dedication ceremonies, I guess.
Yes.
Were you able to?
Yes, I was there.
With all of my
folks okay I have tried to make a good citizen and I have been engaged in a good many civic and other activities but the one of the outside activities that
I am proud of is the opportunity I had to serve on the Governors Committee of 25 to study the education beyond the high school.
It took 14 months.
Another experience that I had that was very satisfying to me was the job that I had as chairman of the Century Committee
to study A&M's program for the future.
And after another 14 months, we submitted a plan to the board of directors, which has been a good eel of it, has been accomplished, and has taken place today.
So you feel like that when you have the opportunity for that experience, you do have some small parts.
and the progress that has taken place.
Somewhere, and I'm not sure from whose office it came, we were able to pick up several boxes of records of the Century Council.
I have looked at them rather hurriedly, I guess I should say.
Do you remember right offhand what the origin of the name Century Council was?
The origin was that by the A&M's 100th birthday, they wanted to set a goal to accomplish at the end of the century, the first century of its history.
I see.
I had it somehow in the back of my mind that it was the century of the Morrill Act, which was in 62 was the centennial of the Morrill Act.
We gave our report 15.
15 years ahead of A&M's 100th birthday.
Now then, the 100th birthday is coming, more than 10 years of that's passed.
So it's coming up, I believe it's 1876.
Yeah, I believe the centennial year is officially to be January through December of 76.
Yes.
So we will be in our 100th year of classes, but
will, in a sense, be riding the coattails of the U.S. bicentennial, which is 200 years for the United States Declaration of Independence.
So you were making a plan for the future that would be accomplished by the centennial.
The theme of our whole study was a plan for excellence.
and we divided our Century Council into groups, committees.
Each one held and recorded all of the proceedings of every meeting, the pros and the cons, and each committee made its report to the council as a whole
Then the council as a whole voted on it, voted for it or against it.
So through that process, we were able to compile a consensus report with no minority report brevity.
Who appointed the Century Council?
They were nominated from all over the state.
They had some 1,200 nominations.
And I'm not sure, but that the board of directors selected them from those nominations.
I believe that's the way it was.
And it was the board then who named you chairman of the council.
Well, possibly the board.
Earl Rudder called me and asked me to take the job.
I would imagine on something like that, at least the board would have approved the selection, if not make it indeed, if they didn't indeed make it themselves.
Yes.

Well, that was... As I said, I have not had the opportunity to thoroughly examine all the records, but I know that there's some correspondence files there, and I think there are some copies of the final report there.
But every...
I'd rather imagine some... Every session was taped and transcribed.
and distributed to the members of the group.
And then we had ample discussion, pro and con, on all of these factors for consideration.
And it was a hard-working group.
We had a high attendance record, and we...
tried to do a good job, and I think we did.
Well, that certainly looks as though you did.
As you said, most of the things which the Century Council recommended had been accomplished, and A&M has certainly shown a substantial amount of development in both quantity and quality.
I was real proud of a communication I got from Jack Williams on the 10th anniversary of the Century Council report.
And he detailed specifics on what had been recommended and what had been accomplished in that 10 years.
Yeah, was this a published brochure?
Yes, it was.
I believe I got one of those for the archives, too.
I'm trying to collect all of these publications that come out as much as possible.
And anything that records anything of significance, I try to collect the copies.
Sometimes it's a little bit difficult to find out
where to get them, but usually with a little perseverance you can do that.
